  <Instrument_Host>
    <name>ROSETTA-LANDER</name>
    <type>Spacecraft</type>
    <naif_host_id>RL</naif_host_id>
    <description>The Philae Lander is a box-shaped unit measuring 850 x 850 x 640 mm, designed to land on a comet using a tripod landing gear secured by harpoons. It has three main parts: an internal compartment for subsystems and experiments, a solar hood housing solar arrays and cameras, and a baseplate with a balcony for direct environmental access. Weighing around 100 kg, it operates with three subsystems on the orbiter for power and data transmission.
 
 The mission requirements include surviving a 10-year cruise with hibernation phases, safe landing on the comet, conducting scientific operations, and long-term monitoring from 3 AU to the Sun. The Lander operates using a power subsystem, data management system, and thermal control system to maintain optimal conditions for its electronics.
 
 Various operational modes exist, including Hibernation, Wake-up, Power Enough, Stand-by, and Operational Modes, each corresponding to specific power states and functionality.</description>
